body:
It is possible that there are unused dependency declarations for the modules, find a way to detect them. The `exclude` statements can also be potentially removed due to new gradle system.
---

I've tried the following two tools but neither of them seemed to work for Android project:

nebula-lint
https://github.com/nebula-plugins/gradle-lint-plugin
It could potentially detect everything needed:
https://github.com/nebula-plugins/gradle-lint-plugin/wiki/All-Dependency-Rule
The comments about this supposed to be working for Android project or not were contradicting.

dependency-analyze
https://github.com/wfhartford/gradle-dependency-analyze

So at this point I don't know if there is any tool we can use.

---

Specifically about the excludes:

'org.dmfs:android-xml-magic' could be updated to use `implementation` for xmlpull, so this exclude could be removed from here:
```
    implementation(d.xml_magic) {
        // xmlpull is part of the runtime, so don't pull it in here
        exclude group: 'xmlpull', module: 'xmlpull'
    }
```

Worth checking if this has been done:
```
    implementation(d.codeka_carrot) {
        exclude module: 'iterators' // TODO Remove when iterators have been removed from codeka:carrot
    }
```

dmfs androd carrot could be updated with `implementation` for this libraries
```
    implementation(d.android_carrot) {
        exclude module: 'carrot'
        exclude group: 'com.android.support'
        exclude module: 'iterators'
        exclude module: 'jems'
    }
```

Could be checked if it works without the exclude now with new gradle system used supposedly in these libraries:
```
    androidTestImplementation(d.support_test_runner) {
        exclude group: 'com.android.support', module: 'support-annotations'
    }
    androidTestImplementation(d.support_test_rules) {
        exclude group: 'com.android.support', module: 'support-annotations'
    }
```

jems could have `implementation` in contentpal modules (or does it have already?)
```
    androidTestImplementation(d.contenttestpal) {
        exclude module: 'jems'
    }
    implementation(d.contentpal) {
        exclude module: 'jems'
    }
    testImplementation(d.contentpal_testing) {
        exclude module: 'jems'
    }
```

I just encountered this once now, not sure how often this can happen.

I was adding tasks quickly with the Quick Add dialog using 'Save and continue' button and then tapped outside of the dialog (while the tasks were also presumably being added to the list UI)

- Tablet (Samsung Galaxy Tab 4), Android 5.0.2
- landscape mode
- on branch `mx/624-task-details-fragment-replace` (TODO PR add number here), but it seems unrelated to the changes there

```
java.lang.NullPointerException: Attempt to invoke virtual method 'java.lang.Object android.support.v4.app.FragmentActivity.getSystemService(java.lang.String)' on a null object reference
    at org.dmfs.tasks.QuickAddDialogFragment$2.run(QuickAddDialogFragment.java:512)
    at android.os.Handler.handleCallback(Handler.java:739)
    at android.os.Handler.dispatchMessage(Handler.java:95)
    at android.os.Looper.loop(Looper.java:145)
    at android.app.ActivityThread.main(ActivityThread.java:6134)
    at java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Native Method)
    at java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:372)
    at com.android.internal.os.ZygoteInit$MethodAndArgsCaller.run(ZygoteInit.java:1399)
    at com.android.internal.os.ZygoteInit.main(ZygoteInit.java:1194)
```

The relevant code part:
```java
    private final Runnable mReset = new Runnable()
    {

        @Override
        public void run()
        {
            mContent.animate().alpha(1).setDuration(250).start();
            mConfirmation.animate().alpha(0).setDuration(250).start();
            mSaveButton.setEnabled(true);
            mSaveAndNextButton.setEnabled(true);

            // reset view
            mEditText.selectAll();

            // bring the keyboard up again
            mEditText.requestFocus();
line:512:   InputMethodManager inputMethodManager = (InputMethodManager) getActivity().getSystemService(Context.INPUT_METHOD_SERVICE);
            inputMethodManager.showSoftInput(mEditText, 0);
        }
    };
```

It seems the `DialogFragment` has detached from the `Activity` by the time this reset runnable was run.

